<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[189,248,267,293]" box="[189,248,267,293]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,248,267,293]" fontSize="11" level="4" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" reason="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,248,267,293]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Note</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[189,1399,313,481]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
The sheet P00477830 is the only specimen upon which the validating diagnosis was based, and it was definitely designated by Bory as the type who mentioned on the sheet ‘N’ for new; according to Art. 9.3 (
<bibRefCitation author="McNeill J. &amp; Barrie F. R. &amp; Buck W. R. &amp; Demoulin V &amp; Greuter D. &amp; Hawksworth L. &amp; Herendeen P. S. &amp; Knapp S. &amp; Marhold K. &amp; Prado J. &amp; Prud'Homme van Reine W. F. &amp; Smith F. &amp; Wiersema J. H. &amp; Turland N. J." box="[197,444,384,410]" journalOrPublisher="Regnum Vegetabile" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" part="154" refString="McNeill J., Barrie F. R., Buck W. R., Demoulin V., Greuter D., Hawksworth L., Herendeen P. S., Knapp S., Marhold K., Prado J., Prud'Homme van Reine W. F., Smith F., Wiersema J. H. &amp; Turland N. J. 2012. International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code). Regnum Vegetabile 154. Koeltz Scientific Books, Koenigstein." title="International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code)" type="journal volume" year="2012">
McNeill 
<emphasis box="[308,372,384,410]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
) this specimen is thus established as the holotype of 
<taxonomicName authority="C.Presl, 1843" authorityName="C.Presl" authorityYear="1843" box="[1111,1267,384,410]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Hymenophyllaceae" genus="Sphaerocionium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Hymenophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pendulum">
<emphasis box="[1111,1267,384,410]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H. pendulum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, rendering unnecessary the projected lectotypification by Pichi Sermolli (notula in Herb. P, September 1967) that was never published and thus is not effective.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[189,1399,519,687]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
In literature (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Tardieu-Blot M. - L." box="[397,614,519,546]" editor="Humbert H." journalOrPublisher="famille" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="16 - 38" part="3" refString="Tardieu-Blot M. - L. 1951. Hymenophyllacees. In: Humbert H. (ed.) Flore de Madagascar et des Comores, famille 3: 16 - 38. MNHN, Paris." title="Hymenophyllacees" type="journal article" volumeTitle="Flore de Madagascar et des Comores" year="1951">Tardieu-Blot 1951</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Tardieu-Blot M. - L." box="[626,689,520,546]" editor="Autrey J. C." journalOrPublisher="IRD editions, Paris. [posthumous publication, revised by F. Badre, MNHN, Paris]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="71 - 90" refString="Tardieu-Blot M. - L. 2008. Hymenophyllacees. In: Autrey J. C., Bosser J. &amp; Ferguson I. K. (eds) Flore des Mascareignes, La Reunion, Maurice, Rodrigues: 71 - 90. IRD editions, Paris. [posthumous publication, revised by F. Badre, MNHN, Paris]." title="Hymenophyllacees" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Flore des Mascareignes, La Reunion, Maurice, Rodrigues" year="2008">2008</bibRefCitation>
), the range of fertile frond length for 
<taxonomicName authority="C.Presl, 1843" authorityName="C.Presl" authorityYear="1843" box="[1119,1259,520,546]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Hymenophyllaceae" genus="Sphaerocionium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Hymenophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="capillare">
<emphasis box="[1119,1259,520,546]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H. capillare</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
varies from (6–)7 to 40 cm long. But in the wild, there are numerous specimens that display minute fertile fronds from 2.5 to 6 cm long, especially those well exposed while the largest and typical specimens usually occur in shadier places (pers. obs.). Such ‘dwarf forms’ are often lacking in collections and we decided here to integrate them in our Xper database as a distinct item.
</paragraph>
